### Regional differences

The ethnic groups used here are for services in England. Different categories are used in Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland.

Services covering more than 1 country should accommodate these differences in their design. For example, by changing the ethnic groups shown depending on whether the user is based in [England](https://gss.civilservice.gov.uk/policy-store/ethnicity/#england), [Wales](https://gss.civilservice.gov.uk/policy-store/ethnicity/#wales-), [Scotland](https://gss.civilservice.gov.uk/policy-store/ethnicity/#scotland) or [Northern Ireland](https://gss.civilservice.gov.uk/policy-store/ethnicity/#northern-ireland).

Where this isn’t possible, services should use the English categories.


### Allowing users to opt out

Users should be able to decline to give their ethnicity.

The preferred option is a separate page asking if users are willing to give their ethnic group, with an explanation of how the data will be used. This should be as specific as possible, for example: ‘we use this information to make sure we’re giving equal opportunities to all candidates’.

Users who do not want to give their ethnicity should be able to finish or exit the service.

### Placement

The question should appear just before, or after, a user has completed your service. For example, using the [check answers pattern](https://design-system.service.gov.uk/patterns/check-answers/), the question appears just before the user checks their answers, or just after they've submitted the form.

### Asking for other protected characteristics

If you ask for other information which is not mandatory, such as gender/sex, consider how to ask for this alongside ethnicity.

You could ask an initial question such as “Will you answer a few more questions so we can monitor this service for equality?” Make sure you explain how all the information will be used.

### Asking a user for someone else’s ethnic group

You should normally not ask users to give someone else’s ethnic group. This is because ethnicity is self-defined. There are some exceptions in the case of young children, for example.

### Data protection

Under the General Data Protection Regulation, there are [different rules](https://ico.org.uk/for-organisations/guide-to-data-protection/guide-to-the-general-data-protection-regulation-gdpr/lawful-basis-for-processing/special-category-data/) around the use and storage of someone’s ethnic origin.

### Check your answers

If a user’s ethnic group will appear in the check answers pattern, you should:

- repeat both options chosen by the user, for example ‘Asian or Asian British: Bangladeshi’
- take the user back to the point at which they could opt out, if they decide to change their answer


## Research on this pattern

### Language

The question ‘What is your ethnic group?’ was agreed following a 2 year cross-government consultation led by the Office for National Statistics.

### Ordering

The order in which the ethnic categories appear on the first page is:

- White
- Mixed or multiple ethnic groups
- Asian or Asian British
- Black or Black British
- another ethnic group

This reflects the most recent figures on the ethnic breakdown of the UK. For example, White is the most common ethnic group in the UK so this appears first. This helps the maximum number of users answer the question as quickly as possible.

The exception is the Mixed and multiple ethnic groups category, which appears second in the list. Testing found that users were more likely to miss this category if it appeared further down the list.

### Write-in option

You should allow users to write in their own ethnicity. Giving users this option has been shown to improve response rates. It can also be a good source of evidence for how ethnic identifications are changing in the long term.

### Two step process

Research by the Office for National Statistics found that presenting all of the ethnic group options on a single page led to some users trying to select more than 1 option. Splitting the question across 2 pages solved this problem across multiple testing rounds with 300+ users.

### Next steps

More research is needed to understand when is the best point within a service to ask this question.
